Design & Analysis workshop

Priscila López-Beltrán Forcada

Spring 2021

In the first part of this workshop, we will cover a series of basic concepts that are crucial to better understand how to design, implement and analyze the results our experiments.

We will start by ensuring that we have a thorough understanding of the characteristics of different types of data, which will be critical before moving on to more advanced topics such as experimental design and data analysis.

Data types

Why is understanding the difference between data types important? Understanding the characteristics of different data types grants us a deeper understanding of (1) the nature of the variables in our experiments and (2) the inter[retation of the results of our experiments.

The most important difference is betweeen quantitative data adn qualitative data. Here is a breakdown with examples:


Let’s now try to identify these data types in a real-life language History Questionnaire data sample

Categorical data vs. Continuous data

Handling continuous data is pretty straight forward, we can apply all types of mathematical functions to them. For example, let see the data set “starwars” in the package “dplyr”. We see that this data set contains variables of many kinds, let’s identify a continuous variable. 

## # A tibble: 6 x 14
##   name  height  mass hair_color skin_color eye_color birth_year sex   gender
##   <chr>  <int> <dbl> <chr>      <chr>      <chr>          <dbl> <chr> <chr> 
## 1 Luke…    172    77 blond      fair       blue            19   male  mascu…
## 2 C-3PO    167    75 <NA>       gold       yellow         112   none  mascu…
## 3 R2-D2     96    32 <NA>       white, bl… red             33   none  mascu…
## 4 Dart…    202   136 none       white      yellow          41.9 male  mascu…
## 5 Leia…    150    49 brown      light      brown           19   fema… femin…
## 6 Owen…    178   120 brown, gr… light      blue            52   male  mascu…
## # … with 5 more variables: homeworld <chr>, species <chr>, films <list>,
## #   vehicles <list>, starships <list>


For instance:

  • Continuous: height

Here we can ask, what is the mean height of all characters?

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
##    66.0   167.0   180.0   174.4   191.0   264.0       6


However, what if we tried to do the same with a categorical variable?

  • Categorical: gender
##    Length     Class      Mode 
##        87 character character


We obviously cannot ask R to give us the mean gender of all characters, and because it reads the vector as class character it won’t tell us much.

What we need to do is create a coding scheme to provide this variable with numerical values.


This is what we call dummy coding, it is basically used to convert categorical variables into a quantitative variables with levels controlled by the researcher.

Our first step is to convert this into a factor using the r,as.factor() function. This creates two levels one for this variable:

## [1] "feminine"  "masculine"

After this, we set masculine as 0, the reference level, an feminine as 1, the alternative level. After this, we can easily calculate the mean of this factor.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
##  0.0000  0.0000  0.0000  0.2048  0.0000  1.0000       4


What we learn from this is that it is absolutely crucial to understand the types of variables in our data sets. Not all data are created equal and treatments may be necessary when we deal with variables that belong to certain data types.

In our next session, we will see that considering the types of data that we deal with will directly impact how we design our experiments. In addition, throughout the course of this workshop, we’ll learn that this will also impact how we analyze, graph and interpret our results.
